comments.body:
@giuseppe so is `fuse-overlay` better? Are there any downside to migrating from the default `metacopy` to `fuse-overlay`?

@martinpitt 
> #16830 was closed as a duplicate. Would you mind retitling this issue to make it easier to find?

I changed the steps-to-reproduce to refer to the other issue. I hesitate to change the title though, because there's a large history of discussion referring to freeze, before it became clear what's the root cause. IMO the best way to handle now that we have your bugreport is to close mine in preference of yours, and then reopen yours one. Anyway, I'd transfer that decision up to maintainers, as well as the question of whether to change the title.

@giuseppe that said, I don't quite understand, what does the command `storage-chown-by-maps` do in this case anyway?

I mean, Idk is there's any side-effects to `--userns=keep-id` option, but the only reason I am using it is to have correct permissions on the bind-mounted directory. That is, if I run a non-root user inside a container, the option makes sure I can access the bind-mounted directory as that user *(otherwise it would be owned by root, hence inaccessible)*.

However, the `storage-chown-by-maps` command clearly runs over some internal container directories, not over the ones bind-mounted. That sounds odd, unless I miss some implementation detail.

In order to make this fast for a rootless user it would take getting idmap support for rootless user.

Another option would be to pull the image in --userns=keep-id mode.
@giuseppe are we capable of doing this? If the user sets userns=keep-id in the containers.conf, we should pull in the correct user namespace, and not have to chown.

@RyanGreenup is machine C *(btrfs)* different in hardware from machine B? I'm asking because if it is, it's hard to judge how much difference is there on native overlay compared to FUSE when BTRFS is involved.

> Using `--userns=keep-id` with Native Overlay does not work on ZFS but it's fine on `btrfs`.

Barring my previous comment, I'd presume the reason for seeing difference in performance may be that BTRFS supports reflinks, whereas ZFS as of today to my knowledge still doesn't.

@Lalufu Isn't fuse-overlayfs the default nowadays?

https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Podman#Enable_native_rootless_overlays

It still is very slow to me, even when using fuse on rootless.

@Hi-Angel Thanks! I'll look this up. It seems to be a lot faster the second time thought.

I'm thinking of creating a caching volume for composer + pnpm - but this doesn't seem to be standard approach?

It would solve my issue thought, because I'm running the same container for multiple services (but with a different role), and I could use a `/cache` volume, to manage the vendor packages.

@giuseppe Hmm, that doesn't look that easy and may break on user changes.

Wouldn't it be possible to integrate `UserNS=keep-id` somehow into the build process?
This would offer a more easier way to build local images (I think).

@giuseppe 
> I'd not worry too much about this problem for now, there is already a workaround with fuse-overlayfs and the last time I talked to Christian Brauner, he said to be interested in getting idmapped mounts working from a user namespace too, and that it was something he was going to work in the near future.

Does this mean that there might eventually be a solution kernel-side for idmapped mounts with unprivileged native overlayfs?

@brauner Is there (still?) a plan for that? If not, what issues would there be with allowing it that don't apply to FUSE overlayfs?
